Flowers demand is subject to changes in people's buying power and ... yes inflation. People are buying less flowers if they struggle to buy groceries.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/
Rosemary, sage and olives have a really long life, they are resistant and essential. They might not be that colorful and they grow slowly, but they never failed to provide a good return even in the most difficult moments.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
A thread on farming

1/
In my small hometown my grandfather was growing sage, olives, laurels and rosemary while every other farmer was growing flowers.
Every year flowers grow quickly and you can sell the entire plant. But then each year you have to grow it back. In a loop.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/
- peer A tries again to establish a conn to B
- peer B tries again to establish a conn to A
- both NATs are instructed now the allow and route packets to each other since these would be respectively considered replies to a self-initiated connection.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/
- connection establishment fails at first
- but now peer A' NATs has a mark that considers packets B->A to be handled as replies to a connection established by A
- and peer B' NATs has a mark that considers packets A->B to be handled as replies to a connection established by A

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/
- peer A tries to establish a conn to B
- peer B tries to establish a conn to A
- peer A's firewall NATs tracks that A wants to connect to B
- peer B's firewall NATs tracks that B wants to connect to A

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/
- peer A wants to connect to peer B
- peer B wants to connect to peer A
- they use a 3rd party node to share with each other their IP/PORT (this 3p node just sends B info to A, and A info to B)

8/
Tether manages the re-issuance phase extremely carefully.
Tether needs to ensure that there are no other claimants, hence there is a delay (of several months) to allow other parties to contact Tether and make their case as well.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
7/
The general process of freezing and re-issuing is extremely thorough (people that went through it can surely confirm it). Compliance and Law Enforcement interactions are mandatory to protect all #Tether  users and Tether Company itself.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/
- a detailed LE confirmation and endorsement is critical because there is no public available information
- claimant needs to go through https://t.co/fB12xESSvB banking grade KYC/AML process
- address(es) don't need to be part of CEX/DEX/DeFi pools, Tether won't affect others

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/
*** General procedure ***
Sometimes Tether users report private hacks / scams and request an address freeze.

ALL information needs to be gathered to Tether via inforequests@tether.to with attached a Law Enforcement letter that confirms the claimant information / request.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/
Frozen funds will be released back to the legitimate owner once there is confirmation / proof of proper actions taken in order to restore security of the bridges.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:

- processing thread (bin trees for books)
- output socket thread

The complicated piece is: resilience and redundancy and data loss prevention.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/
Tether can provide a blueprint for how a CBDC could work. Still, CBDCs might not be issued on a blockchain like Ethereum. Rather, they may be deployed on permissioned blockchain technology rather than the permissionless blockchain on which USDt runs.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@mikekelly85 @bitfinex Or maybe @bitfinex avoiding AWS, using dedicated infra + multiple locations, custom failover, not relying on someone's else magic, is what saves @bitfinex from having frequent issues. ie. yesterday many exchanges went down because AWS had issues.
Do it yourself pays over time.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@mikekelly85 @bitfinex If you have random reboots, especially on the matching engine, a single truth source for exchanges, you can of course fail over, but there is a lot of follow-up checking to do to ensure no message got lost etc.
When you deal with people's money, predictability is important.

Seneca: "Gladiator in arena consilium capit" - "the gladiator is formulating his plan in the arena". Or, if you wait to formulate your plan until you're about to enter battle, you are too late.
Or, don't wait for the next crypto-barbarian horde to prepare your infrastructure.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
8/
Infrastructure (2):
-  2x frontend servers to support many more websocket sessions and concurrent REST requests, while optimizing the API services codebase to scale up to 10x/20x.
- sub-microsecond switches

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
7/
Infrastructure (1):
- doubling the cabinets: more backend / data-warehouse / data processing servers to handle / archive historical information and serve hist API requests
(handling/storing/serving 1billion + trading events per day requires a lot of careful planning)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/
Matching engine (2):
- optimize cross-FX virtual books
- reduce mutexes to the bare minimum
- simplify codebase and more automated tests coverage

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/
Bitfinex's Road to Rome upgrade has different targets.

Matching engine (1):
- reduce number of internal queues that messages have to traverse
- increase in-process sharding across multiple threads
- UDP multicast more heavily used

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/
In a trading platform the matching engine is the central process where all the data flows, gets processed and then departs to get back to the 4 corners of the World (literally, since our traders are located everywhere). Hence the parallelism with Rome.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:

Still today, if you walk in Rome, you can feel the wisdom, the strength and the magnificence of what was, once upon a time, the most powerful city in the world.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/
Using these roads, merchants, citizens and soldiers were gathering to Rome to trade, talk politics, make decisions for the future of the Empire and prepare for the next conquer.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
1/
The upcoming version of @bitfinex matching engine has code-name: Road To Rome.
Why? In the Roman empire all the "Viae" (Roads) where leading to Rome, the center of the known World.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
8/
Benefit (2):
- reliable UDP multicast
- bare-metal Linux installs
- you're the only one using your CPU (see spectre-like attacks)
- colocation services offering

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
7/
Benefit (1):
- the entire infra behavior is predictable
- RAID enabled historical sharded data-warehouses kick asses
- KYD, KYM and KYC 😅: Know Your Disk, Know your Mem and Know Your CPU
- dedicated switches and firewalls, back to back connectivity for core servers

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/
Path to metal 🤘🤘🤘
Our infra team has outstanding experience in secure, god wrath resistant, deployments, so we discussed a lot about pros and cons.

Here are the 2 cons summarized:
- hardware decay
- physical hosts maintenance (trips to datacenter, hardware expertise, ...)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/
Problems (4):
- reliable UDP multicast: AWS seems not to support UDP multicast, while GC does not. Anyway what's the expected packet loss? 
- security: spectre attacks, data hosted on 3rd party, ...
- #crypto is growing. When next bull run? How to ensure 10x/100x scalability

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/
Problems (3):
- disk throughput can be throttled (GP2, IO1)
- if you use SSDs on cloud, which model do you have, are you the only writer?, how to get a proper RAID setup?, ...
- how to minimize the number of switches between your instances?
- unpredictable network behaviors

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/
Problems (2):
- handling billions of events per day and recording them it's one of the main bottlenecks of (crypto) exchanges -> DBMS have to record 100k events per second sustained?
- on cloud you're not sure how CPU gets allocated (trading engine is a CPU bound process)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/
Problems (1):
- order/execution full roundtrip should be ~1ms or lower, should be improved over time (0.1ms target)
- mange 10k+ to 100k+ orders/sec
- recording to historical data stores all events, available to users via API and UI

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:

Till Jan 2018 Bitfinex was using cloud hosting providers (AWS) as main site for the platform.
We soon figure out that was almost impossible to scale a CEX on cloud.
Here is the train of thoughts that we had in the mighty infrastructure team.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/
Why an agnostic payment layer and not yet another single-purpose coin?
Because network protocols and payment layers should be decoupled.
TCP/IP does not need a token. But you can create TCP/IP based apps that require payments.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/
Hence @dazaar_com is the perfect framework to build any kind of decentralized, resilient, reliable and UNSTOPPABLE application.
Yes, unstoppable, yet not blockchain based. 🤯🤯🤯🤯
And you can monetize your apps, thanks to the agnostic micropayments layer

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@DoveyWan No problem!
I think the issue was just timing.
When users reduce their positions it takes a bit of time to process closed loans and return funds to lenders to be lent out again.
The massive size + this accounting delay caused lending books to be temporarily wiped out.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
(Today my english is worse than usual)

Notes: 
- P2P lending books are run by users as normal trading books, based on demand and offer
- P2P lending books are not a representation of BFX own USD balance sheet, but BFX users lending the USD they have in their accounts

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
(Repost to clarify due to some comment idiocy)

This is not correct on multiple levels:
- BFX does not own Tether
- BFX peer-to-peer lending books has run out of USD (not USDt) due to big users re-balancing their longs against USD, causing around 700M in lending to be refreshed.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: Note 2: running out of USD in the P2P lending market means that there are not offers available to be taken.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: Note: after the re-balancing finished, USD P2P lending books got back again in a situation of full liquidity.

Pro-tips
- use an airgapped computer for the entire process
- store backup of your PGP key somewhere safe (follow same practice you use for your #bitcoin seed)
- test backup periodically
- use a strong PIN for the Yubikey

tweet:

You can then use your Yubikey with SSH to login to password-less login to servers, decrypt/encrypt files, ... all without ever accessing directly the PGP private key.

@planb4v @bitfinex You have different options. If you claim the long you'll return exactly were you are of course.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@planb4v @bitfinex Imagine to have 1 BTC in your wallet.
You can create 1 BTCUSD long at (e.g) @ 19000.
The account will change as following
a) 1 BTCUSD long @ 19000 (base price)
b) 1 BTC will be deducted from your wallet
c) 19000 USD will be added to your wallet

Every context switch requires time to gain the best focus level that you need, a bit like in the CPU registries get overwritten by the memory required by the current process.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:

Expanding on Lesson #1.
The brain is like a CPU.

If you have multiple monitors (news, slack, telegram, ...), every time something change on a screen your eye/brain will notice that and you'll initiate a context switch.
And then you'll have to context switch back.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:

#2 lessons to improve coding

Lesson #1: do not use multiple monitors, use a single laptop sized monitor, you'll use 100% of your brain always on the current task only.

Lesson #2: follow lesson #1.

tweet:
@hasufl @udiWertheimer 2/
CEX matching engines use a thread per pair to increase efficiency, so a cascade-FOK would require a mutex that locks X threads in order to complete.
TLDR: it would be bad.
I'll think about it a bit more. Tricky to make it working without counterparty risk for the CEX

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@hasufl @udiWertheimer 1/
It could be solved by a new order type that we could call cascade-FOK.
The system calculates a possible route crossing multiple pairs and tries to execute all the different legs atomically. Either all succeed or none.
ERC20 has that behavior embedded in smart contracts.

10/10

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
9/10
Unfortunately at that time #bitcoin did not exist yet (it was around 2003/2004), otherwise I could have structured in-game growth goodies paid in sats and maybe organize contests with a prize in $BTC

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
8/10
After a year or so I started working on another really amazing project and decided to sell warwide to a sexy shop owner that loved the game 😊 🍌🥔

The website is still there https://t.co/fnWCr0qYNM but not sure if the game is still active. https://t.co/rTcUkknjj3

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
7/10
Lot of gamers started to use it and contributed with great ideas to increase strategies complexity, in-game weapons, ...

I had a lot of fun.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/10
I had to build a really complex in-memory data structure (entire earth boundaries) in order to calculate where tanks/ships could move (land vs sea).
High-performance calculation and movement prediction had to be perfect in order to offer a smooth experience.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/10
* gamers could create alliances to help defending a bigger territory

Technically it was quite challenging.

For the base game UI I used https://t.co/yFrZBeBNCr + openstreetmap + jQuery. Backend was mainly PHP + MySQL + C (for the location service)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/10
* gamers could move their armies by land (tanks, soliders, ...) or by sea (ships, ...) and conquer other cities
* army movement on earth or by sea was calculated at actual travel pace (100 km/h) so it could take days to reach a target city https://t.co/44IGHrLO4z

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/10
It was actually a really complex game.
* set on a real world map
* gamers could pick any real city in the world (I used a db of cities with their coords) to establish their headquarters
* they could build factories, an army with many different weapons (tanks, ships, ...)
...

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/10
When I was 18 (2003/2004 ish), at my university, lot of my colleagues were playing to browser games, so I said "I can do a better browser game" (I was just a little tiny bit cocky)

I loved table strategy games like Risk so I decided to create a browser MMORPG called WarWide https://t.co/w32jsUzpCk

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
1/10

Yesterday I was part of a great interview (it will be released soon) and we briefly discussed my background / history as a developer.
It made me re-think to all the projects I developed in my career and a really particular one came to my mind.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@aeyakovenko @SBF_Alameda @DecentralStn @seb_alameda This is similar to the block size debate in bitcoin.

Of course in 10 years you can have a 100GB block, but why you would do that if you can scale more elegantly?

Same applies here.
You might be able to scale putting tons of hardware but there are better ways :-)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@aeyakovenko @SBF_Alameda @DecentralStn @seb_alameda In 10 year we might see that.
But it would mean that every single node / participant to the network has to have outstanding network speed and resources.
Till today in most of the world 1Gb/s is still a dream.
Isn't it better to avoid L1 having to handle it all?

tweet:
@SBF_Alameda @DecentralStn @aeyakovenko @seb_alameda Problem reaching 10M txs per second is more on the network side.

Maybe on a local machine, but on a distributed geographic net?

You could create 100 shards and have inter-shard sync, but then the chatter across shards might be too high with block time < 1s

tweet:

Why it happens? If L1 is fast and cheap people will think they can use it for anything: storage, gambling, sending money, selling horses and sheeps. Then you'll need anyway L2 solutions to break bottlenecks. It's just a function of time and success

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@SBF_Alameda 1/2 
Eventually a L1 will saturate. Only way to increase throughput is to use L2 solutions. Even if you have a L1 chain that can do 10M txs second, it will just delay the moment it will saturate and you'll have to move to L2.

tweet:
4/4

Unstoppable DEX: P2P (mix of BitTorrent and Lightning Network, thousands of small exchanges / books / ownerships / deployments), direct TCP/IP networking model (no blockchain transport layer), blockchain settlements, hubs are just data/book aggregators

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/4
More issues
- while a blockchain is "decentralised" and made by many nodes, the contract is uniquely identified by a hash, hence centralised around a single group in the eyes of regulators
- can suffer of different types of hacks, still single point of failure

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/4 current DEXes are exciting but just temporary solutions
Few of the issues

- single managed smart contracts
- single governance group / token
- no KYC
- slow
- highly dependent from a single chain and its fees
- faster blockchains are more centralised
....

tweet:

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@marketcapone LE and normal order insertion use 2 different queues.
LE has a priority queue, to not use the same one of general order insertion.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @marketcapone Why? Not sure from where you deducted that. Users get liquidated only when they should. The system is just more scalable.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
7/7
* Complexity of this solution relies in write tests (we have more than 1000 automated simulations running)
* Happy to elaborate if not really clear.
* These are the types of solutions used in huge brokers with M of customers. No much way around it.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
6/7
* When a LEO gets processed, the OB thread evaluates (querying UD) if the user should still be liquidated and using which LS.
* We tested this system with 100sK users + apocalyptic cascading liquidations and ended up always in ensuring the 0-sum game

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
5/7
* Depending on the size of the position to be liquidated, LEO can be run into the book or positions can be acquired by the system and sold via more complex algos. We call it liquidation stages (LS).

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
4/7
* Each LE sorts users by risk (probability of getting liquidated).
* Improvement: a single shared sorted map can be generated across the threads

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/7
* LE interacts with OB via in-mem priority queue.
* LE adds to a liquidation-order (LEO) enough meta-info for the order book thread to evaluate if liquidation should still happen, bankruptcy price, ...

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/7
* The order book (OB) for each pair is run on a single thread, with its own I/O queues.
* User data UD is deterministically sharded among different threads 
* Liquidation engine (LE) is a set of threads with direct mem access to user data threads (positions, balances, ..)

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
1/7
Problem: How to scale trading/liquidation engines up to 500k/1M/10M users? 100k users are manageable, but eventually single threaded architecture will bottleneck growing number of users.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
Sharding users among multiple threads in the matching engine allows running concurrent liquidation engines, one per shard. Can't scale unless you go parallel.
#bitfinex

All the processes are in the clear and @Tether_to has always publicly explained this model.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
#tether authorization security model
1/2 Authorizing on a chain means that Tether signers needs to access private keys. We don't want signers to access those keys so frequently (many times per day). That's why we do a bulk authorization to replenish the inventory.

tweet: @lowstrife @SBF_Alameda Yes, opacity leads to unpredictability

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @lowstrife @SBF_Alameda Also we picked a datacenter nearby (150m) the new Swiss Google Cloud infrastructure, so you still have that benefit.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @lowstrife @SBF_Alameda Regarding peering HFT requires cross-connect and colo. This will reduce latency drastically. You can see that AWS is suboptimal here too, since you can peer from same region but pass through undetermined number of hops and hardware.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @lowstrife @SBF_Alameda CPU and multithreading can be achieved with metal instances. But cost is 3 times having the same setup in your rack. Also problem is more: 1. Ability to connect servers back to back. 2. pick your own selected hardware switches and firewalls. 3. distance between hosts 4. disks

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @lowstrife @SBF_Alameda AWS conf is opaque from what I experienced. Unless you know details you can't go HF. We use raid10 (8 disk) setup on all servers. And back to back connectivity is key for efficient replica. If you get a server with 70+ cores + 8 SSDs on AWS you're paying them new every 5 months.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
@taipancapital @SBF_Alameda Indeed. We have cameras all around the racks. Locked room with pin etc. It really feels better.
AWS is great for a start but try to have mongo or mysql writing at high speed. You'll want to hang yourself after few days

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @SBF_Alameda 1/2 The lie is more subtle. You can easily create a matching engine that have that perf. 2 red-black tries + binary UDP I/O. The real lie is that most of exchanges can't handle writing, reconciling and distributing data at that speed: internal distribution, DB I/O, user delivery

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @Mikefletcher42 Scaling is just for pairs/processes to overcome limit of CPUs in a single machine. A pair is only handled by a single process. The benefit of sharding a pair would be lost using network mutex

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @Mikefletcher42 A single symbol process can handle up to 350k orders/sec. We're improving towards 1M per process. Also having native sharding support let us scale horizontally in a cluster, giving almost infinite matching power.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @cyrii_MM @IamNomad For queues you can use ZMQ or pure TCP. Nasdaq uses reliable multicast (UDP) for data streams. It's something we're experimenting as well but not in production yet. Data structures: red black trees or avl trees are what you need for actual in memory matching

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet: @IamNomad Indeed. It shall be comprehensive

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
3/3 Many exchanges rely on traditional databases to handle matching. This is why during peak market activity they won't perform well and throughput is heavily limitated.
Of course it requires to develop custom fault-tolerance, resilience, ... but it's simply the only correct way.

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
2/3 Then how you make it resilient, super-scalable, micro-second fast, ... it's all about art.
I spent quite sometime in developing @bitfinex 's one, via many iterations and experiments.
Now it's a beautiful beast, capable of incredible performance and powering several products!

name: Paolo Ardoino 🕳🥊
tweet:
1/3 I should, at some point, make a small tutorial about matching engines.
You can write a really really simple one in few lines of code.
ZMQ-input -> matching (2 red black trees per symbol) -> ZMQ-output
